<FIRST>r a AM-InsecticideCurb 1stLd-Writethru a0417 03-21 0421</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Insecticide Curb, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0417,0426</SECOND>
<HEAD>EPA Scientists Want To Ban Widely Used Insecticide</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: RECASTS lead to reflect that EPA scientists want to bar use,
with no decision made by agency as a whole.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>'NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Scientists at the Environmental Protection Agency
want to bar the use of a highly toxic insecticide on potatoes and
imported bananas because its residue poses a health risk to infants
and children, according to a published report.
   The recommendation to restrict use of the insecticide aldicarb
was made on Jan. 12 by toxicologists from the EPA's pesticide
division, The New York Times reported in Tuesday's editions.
   The uses of aldicarb on 10 other crops would be allowed to
continue under the panel's proposal because the chemical is not used
as heavily on those crops and does not leave as much residue as it
does on potatoes and bananas, according to a copy of the EPA's
recommendation obtained by the Times.
   But the report said the risks ``exceed the benefits when aldicarb
is used on bananas and potatoes.'' The other crops were peanuts,
oranges, grapefruit, limes, sugar cane, soybeans, dried beans,
sorghum, pecans and coffee.
   The document said 15,000 to 50,000 infatO and children a day are
exposed to enough aldicarb to present a risk of getting ill from
eating potatoes.
   One drop of aldicarb absorbed through the skin can kill an adult,
The Times said. In children, exposure in the concentrations found in
some potatoes could cause stomach cramps, nervous disorders,
headaches and other ailments.
   Bananas were said to present a risk to as many as 1,500 infants
and children.
   In 1985, more than 1,000 people reported getting sick in eight
Western states and Canada from California-grown watermelons
contaminated with the chemical.
   The use of aldicarb has been restricted for years in New York,
Rhode Island and Wisconsin because of contamination of underground
water supplies. The EPA has found the chemical, known by its trade
name Temik, in ground water in 22 states. It is used widely in
Idaho, Maine and Washington, the three biggest potato-producing
states.
   Mary Anne Ford, a spokeswoman for Rhone-Poulenc S.A., the French
company that manufactures aldicarb, denied that the chemical is a
hazard on any food crops.
   ``That data does not reflect any risk to any group including
infants and children,'' she said.
   The EPA toxicologists' recommendation was presented to Dr. John
A. Moore, now acting deputy administrator of the agency. He has not
made a formal response to the report, the Times said.
</TEXT>
