<HEAD>Clark Officially Announces Sabbatical From Eastside High</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PATERSON, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Joe Clark, the high school principal who is
the subject of a hit film depicting his disciplinary methods,
officially announced Monday he will take a paid, six-month
sabbatical.
   Clark, known for carrying a baseball bat and addressing students
at Eastside High School with a bullhorn, said he is considering
writing a book, and is talking with the Bush administration about a
job in Washington. His leave would start in September.
   Don Hamilton, a spokesman for William Bennett, President Bush's
drug czar, said Monday there had been ``preliminary discussions with
Joe Clark, who is an old friend of Bill Bennett's, but no job offer
has been made.''
   Bennett, who was secretary of education in the Reagan
administration, helped bring Clark to national attention last year
with his praise of the principal's get-tough methods.
   But Clark has also been criticized, particularly in the last few
weeks because of a strip show performed during a school assembly
while he was out of town. He approved the show, but says he knew
nothing about the partial nudity. He was suspended for five days.
   Clark made his first announcement of his sabbatical late Friday
through a spokesman but spoke publicly about his decision for the
first time Monday at an early morning news conference on the steps
of his school.
   He blasted the Paterson City Council, which tried to fire him
because of the incident.
   ``In no way am I leaving because of a bunch of impish, insincere
and diabolical council members,'' he said.
   He didn't say if he would return to Eastside after his sabbatical.
   ``I wish him luck,'' said School Board President Elease Evans.
``Eastside will miss Joe Clark. However, Eastside will go on.''
   ``I think Mr. Clark is emotionally and physically exhausted,''
she said, adding that he would bg@velcomed if he wants to return.
   Clark has been busy promoting his hit film, ``Lean On Me,'' which
features his efforts to improve education at the troubled,
drug-ridden school.
