<HEAD>Sobbing Hawke Tells Nation He Committed Adultery</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD BILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SYDNEY, Australia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Bob Hawke, dogged by
questions about his personal life, has tearfully admitted in a
television interview to being unfaithful to his wife of 33 years.
   Hawke told the Channel 7 network's Newsworld program he has
committed adultery but said would do so no longer. Hawke, tears
welling in his eyes, said he loved his wife, Hazel, whom he called
an ``incredible woman.''
   The Labor Party leader said ``she understood that it was part of
a pretty volatile, exuberant character, and she knew my love for her
had never changed.'' He also made references to his past drinking
problems.
   The interview was to be broadcast nationally tonight.
   Hawke must call elections in mid-1990 and he has said he will
seek an unprecedented fourth three-year term as prime minister. His
popularity is believed to be eroding because of rising interest
rates, higher taxes and other economic woes.
   The 59-year-old premier has been followed by questions about his
personal life for years but had never admitted he cheated on his
wife. His stunning confession on national television caused a
sensation.
   ``Bob Hawke In Tears: How I Cheated On Hazel,'' read the headline
in the Sydney Morning Herald. It carried a cartoon portraying Hawke
saying to his wife as she fills in a ballot in a voting booth,
``I've been unfaithful! Do you still love me?''
   Opposition Liberal Party leader John Howard refused comment on
Hawke's admission. Deputy Prime Minister Lionel Bowen said he found
it ``interesting'' but did not elaborate.
   Clover Moore, an independent member of the Sydney Council, said
she thought many women would be angry about infidelity admission.
   ``I think it's very cruel of him to publicly humiliate his
wife,'' she said. ``I think the majority of women would think it is
in very bad taste to put Hazel through such a public demonstration.''
   The couple celebrated their 33rd wedding anniversary two weeks
ago.
   The interview was the second time Hawke has broken down on
national television while making a personal admission. In 1984, he
began crying when he referred to drug problems among members of his
family.
   Mrs. Hawke later went on television to explain that their
daughter, Roslyn, and her husband, Matt, had been treated for heroin
addiction.
   Hawke gave no details about his sexual liaisons in the interview,
a transcript of which was released by both Channel 7 and the prime
minister's office.
   A spokesman for Hawke said the admission was not new. ``All this
has been said before,'' said the official, who is not allowed to be
named.
   In the interview, journalist Clive Robertson asked Hawke what
people mean when they accuse him of being a womanizer.
   ``They mean I was unfaithful to my wife,'' Hawke replied.
   Robertson: ``Is that true?''
   Hawke: ``Yes.''
   Robertson: ``Did you stop that?''
   ``Yes,'' Hawke replies in tears, and then, ``I guess there are
not many women who would have put up with me all that time. But my
love for her never changes. I have always loved Hazel, always will.
   Hawke also referred to his past drinking, which his biographer
Blanche d'Alpuget says earned him an entry in the Guinness Book of
Records when he drank 2{ pints of beer in 12 seconds while 3udying
at Oxford University in Britain.
   ``I was never an alcoholic in the sense that I couldn't work,''
said Hawke, who has said he stopped drinking alcohol in 1979. ``I
always worked very hard. It was getting to the stage where at the
end of the day I was looking forward too much to a drink. I thought
that was pretty unintelligent.''
</TEXT>
