<SECOND>PM-US-El Salvador, Bjt,550</SECOND>
<HEAD>Democrats to Try To Condition Salvador Aid</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   State Department officials are bracing for
their toughest fight with Congress in years over aid to El Salvador
following presidential elections won by the most right-wing
candidate.
   House Democrats have told the administration they will attempt to
impose tight conditions on aid to El Salvador in hopes of pressuring
the country to improve its human rights performance and negotiate
peace with leftist guerrillas.
   One Democratic faction, led by Rep. David Obey, D-Wis., would
release the aid in increments, threatening to cut off the money at
any time if El Salvador does not meet requirements set forth in
legislation.
   A State Department official, insisting on anonymity, called this
approach ``unbelievable micromanagement'' on Monday and said the
administration will attempt to keep the aid program as free of
conditions as possible.
   Obey, chairman of the House Appropriations subcommittee on
foreign operations, was not available Monday for comment on his
legislative plans.
   Secretary of State James A. Baker III was expected to be asked
about the aid issue today during testimony before a House Foreign
Affairs subcommittee.
   In El Salvador, the Arena party candidate, Alfredo Cristiani, won
a lopsided victory over Fidel Chavez Mena of the ruling Christian
Democratic party in Sunday's election.
   The United States has provided $3.5 billion in aid to El Salvador
during this decade but many lawmakers are becoming restive about
increasing human rights violations there and government's inability
to negotiate a settlement to the war.
   Adding to the concern is that the Arena party has been linked to
rightist death squads. One of the most prominent leaders in the
party is Roberto D'Aubuisson, who was described by former U.S.
Ambassador Robert White as a ``pathological killer.'' In 1980, the
Carter administration stripped D'Aubuisson of his U.S. visa.
   Cristiani insists he'll be his own man as president and will not
be beholden to D'Aubuisson and his allies. The success of the
administration in obtaining approval for Salvador aid without
conditions depends on Cristiani's ability to disassociate himself
from D'Aubuisson, according to government officials.
   The administration contends that the Farabundo Marti National
Liberation guerrilla movement has refused to enter into serious
negotiations on ending the war. As for rights abuses, officials
contend that politically motivated killings are only a small
fraction of what they were in the 1980-82 period.
   Until 1984, the Reagan administration endured one clash with
C/oress after another over aid to El Salvador because of widespread
rights violations. It was not until the election of President Jose
Napoleon Duarte in 1984 that the administration was able to win
bipartisan support on that issue.
   The State Department said Monday it is prepared to continue
supporting El Salvador but only so long as the government respects
democracy and protects human rights.
   Department spokesman Charles Redman praised the Salvadoran people
for having braved ``violence and terror'' which he blamed on the
guerrillas.
   At least 29 guerrillas and soldiers were killed in fighting
Sunday, as well as two civilians. Three journalists _ two
Salvadorans and a Dutchman _ also were killed by government security
forces over the election weekend.
   At the White House, presidential spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said
judgments about human rights will be a ``very important factor'' in
guiding U.S. policy toward El Salvador.
</TEXT>
